## Non-Negotiable Rules

These are enforced by hooks where possible â€” the bullets below are advisory reminders, not primary enforcement.

- **No AI attribution anywhere** â€” never mention AI, Claude, OpenAI, agent names, or TDD phases in commits, PR descriptions, code comments, documentation, or any project artifact. No `Co-Authored-By: Claude`, no `Generated with` footers, no references to AI tools. Enforced by the `no-ai-attribution.sh` hook.
- **No hardcoded secrets** â€” environment variables only; fail-fast at startup if a required variable is absent; never log secrets. Enforced by the `security-guard.sh` hook.
- **No `print()` in library code** (Python) / **no `console.log` in `src/`** (TypeScript) â€” structured logging only.
- **No bare `except:`** (Python) â€” catch specific exceptions.
- **No deprecated `typing.Dict` / `typing.List`** (Python 3.10+) â€” use `dict`, `list`, `X | None`.
- **No `any` without justification** (TypeScript) â€” strict mode enforced by `tsc`.
- **Parameterised SQL only** â€” no string interpolation, no f-strings, no template literals with user input.
- **Coverage floors** â€” â‰Ą95% for Python, â‰Ą80% for TypeScript, on all changed files.
- **ESLint flat config must exist** in every TypeScript repo. The Stop hook blocks completion when an `eslint.config.*` exists and changed files have lint errors.

---

## Commit Standard (Conventional Commits)

Format: `{type}({scope}): {description}` â€” types: `feat` `fix` `refactor` `test` `docs` `chore`.
Breaking change: add `!` before `:`.

- **Never** mention TDD phases, agent names, or AI in commit messages.
- **Never** add AI attribution (`Co-Authored-By: Claude`, `Generated with`, etc.).
- **Never** reference planning artefacts or internal labels in PR descriptions.

---

## Branch Rules

**NEVER commit directly to `main` / `master`. Always use a feature branch.**

- One branch per logical unit of work.
- Branch must be pushed to `origin` and a PR opened before merging.
- PR must pass all CI status checks before merge.
- Delete the branch locally and remotely after merge.

<!-- CUSTOMISE: optional â€” if you use a ticketing system, add a branch-naming rule here. -->
<!-- Example: `{type}/<PROJ>-{N}/{short-description}` â€” one ticket per branch. -->

---

## Observability Standards

Every new action, probe, or service endpoint must:

- Emit an OTel span with appropriate attributes (no PII, no secrets).
- Use structured logging only â€” no `print()`, no credentials in output.
- Follow a consistent metric naming convention (`<service>_<component>_<metric>_<unit>`).

